  "prompt": "What is compression ratio in engine?",
  "response": "The compression ratio in an engine is a measure of how much the air-fuel mixture is compressed within the engine's combustion chamber during the compression stroke. Specifically, it is defined as the ratio of the maximum cylinder volume (when the piston is at the lowest point, or Bottom Dead Center) to the minimum cylinder volume (when the piston is at the highest point, or Top Dead Center).\n\nMathematically, it is expressed as:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Compression Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Volume at BDC}}{\\text{Volume at TDC}}\n\\]\n\nFor example, if the volume at Bottom Dead Center (BDC) is 600 cc and the volume at Top Dead Center (TDC) is 100 cc, the compression ratio would be:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Compression Ratio} = \\frac{600\\, \\text{cc}}{100\\, \\text{cc}} = 6:1\n\\]\n\nHigher compression ratios generally lead to more efficient combustion and improved engine performance, as they allow for more power to be generated with less fuel. However, higher compression ratios can also increase the likelihood of engine knocking (pre-ignition), which can be detrimental to engine performance and longevity. As a result, the compression ratio is an important design parameter that balances performance, efficiency, and fuel type requirements.",
